[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.  The Government favours a stan
[normal]dard medical report form for use in all claims, but
[normal]this will inevitably mean that reporting doctors would have to confine their  remarks to a standard template or a drop-box option which will limit the amount of     information provided.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.  
[normal]              
[normal]Lack of det
[normal]ail will not advance the Government’s objective of address
[normal]ing 
[normal]fraud. The 
[normal]r
[normal]eporting expert must be free to describe in his own words the claimant’s account 
[normal]o
[normal]f his injuries, how they affected him and for how long. There must also be an
[normal] 
[normal]opportunity
[normal] 
[normal]for the expert to provide 
[normal]his 
[normal]impressions
[normal] 
[normal]of the claimant and the account he has provided.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.  The Government also favours a system in which the medical report is sent 
[normal]simultaneously
[normal] to the claimant and defendant. This is completely inappropriate as medi
[normal]cal reports contain confidential medical information
[normal],
[normal] requir
[normal]ing
[normal] the individual’s informed consent
[normal] 
[normal]before being passed to a third party.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Pre-medical offers[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]9.   A
[normal]PIL has argued from the outset that offers of compensation made to claimants without a 
[normal]medical report should be banned
[normal], and we were therefore enormously encouraged by the comments of the Transport Select Committee and the Government in relation to this
[normal]. The APIL research 
[normal]referred to in paragraph 5 
[normal]found that half of respondents questioned be
[normal]lieved that this practice 
[normal]is in itself fraudulent. We were  encouraged, therefore, to hear from the Association of British Insurers recently that “the industry is willing to consider stopping pre-med offers…”
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10.
[normal]              
[normal]It is unfortunate that this sentiment 
[normal]was conditional on other developments, but still represents welcome progress, particularly when some in the industry have expressed their disquiet publicly about the practice
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11. I
[normal]t is
[normal] is clear that t
[normal]his practice should be banned by means of legislation
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]here 
[normal]are
[normal], however,
[normal] rule changes which c
[normal]an 
[normal] 
[normal]be 
[normal]introduced
[normal] 
[normal]more 
[normal]quickly
[normal] 
[normal]which 
[normal]will
[normal] help to change behaviour in relation to this practice and we are, at the time of writing
[normal], 
[normal] in dialogue
[normal] with the Government
[normal] on necessary changes
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12. 
[normal]A
[normal] medical report should not be required at the very beginning of the claim process
[normal] as a
[normal] requirement to produce a medical report at the outset would generate unnecessary costs and delays in claims which do not proceed.   
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]13. O
[normal]nce
[normal] an improved system of med
[normal]ical reporting 
[normal]has been
[normal] developed, it must be used. 
[normal] 
[normal]While the practice of pre-medical offers persists in whiplash cases, fraud can continue undetected. To stop fraud, pre-medical offers must be banned, and the quality of medical reporting must be higher –
[normal] the two will work in tandem.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14. 
[normal]Third party capture is another route by which fraud can take place undetected. Insurers should also commit to obtaining medical evidence
[normal] if
[normal] dealing with people direct.
[normal] Injured people must be protected from 
[normal]the 
[normal]abuses whic
[normal]h do take place when insurers deal with the
[normal]m
[normal] direct, including 
[normal]the exertion of 
[normal]undue influence and inequality of information and bargaining power.
[normal] 
[normal]     
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fraud d[bold]ata [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]15. 
[normal]C
[normal]laimant lawyers 
[normal]can
[normal] be gatekeepers against people who try to make fraudulent claims if relevant information held by the insurance industry 
[normal]is
[normal] made available to 
[normal]them
[normal]. 
[normal]Claimant solicitors could be of 
[normal]real 
[normal]value in the fight against fraud if they  have access to the number and 
[normal]type of accidents 
[normal]in which 
[normal]a potential client has been involved, and 
[normal]information about 
[normal]personal injury claims arising from them.
[normal] This information is currently held by insurers
[normal] and there is no logical disadvantage to it being made available to claimant soli
[normal]citor
[normal]s
[normal].
[normal] The date any previous injur
[normal]y was
[normal] 
[normal]sustained would also be very helpful as, if the case is genuine, this information could assist medical professionals to provide the best treatment for patient
[normal]s
[normal]. 
[normal]We are greatly encouraged
[normal] to learn 
[normal]that discussions
[normal] about 
[normal]this are ongoing in the insurance industry
[normal] and that information may become available in due course
[normal].
[normal] Ideally, this data would need to be available at the time of implementation of the new medical reporting system.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Small Claims Court Limit[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]16. 
[normal]The announcement that there would be no change to the small claims court limit at this 
[normal]time
[normal] was very much welcomed by AP
[normal]IL. T
[normal]he small claims court was not designed for people who represent themselves in personal injury cases; raising the limit would have h
[normal]ad no impact on fraud whatsoever, 
[normal]and this was, after all, 
[normal]a 
[normal]key
[normal] 
[normal]purpose 
[normal]of the Government’s consultation; it would have had an enormous 
[normal]and negative 
[normal]impact on the courts, which would have been overwhelmed by litigants in person who would have struggled to
[normal] understand the court system; and it would have led to another explosion of spam calls and texts from claims management companies who would have exploited the situation of people who would no longer be able to afford legal representation.
[normal] A
[normal]n increase
[normal] in th
[normal]e limit would
[normal], therefore,
[normal] 
[normal]have 
[normal]be
[normal]en
[normal] wholly counterproductive
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]17. 
[normal]It is to be hoped that proposals can now be developed which will assist all concerned in ensuring fair compensation for those 
[normal]injured people
[normal], while working to eradicate fraudulent
[normal] and exa
[normal]g
[normal]g
[normal]erated claims.
